IV. Evaluating Our Understanding of Recovery and Preventing Relapse -- tSEVENTEEN. FUTURE DIRECTIONS IN SUBSTANCE ABUSE RELAPSE AND RECOVERY -- tINDEX0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn this book leading experts in the field of addictions report on key aspects of addictive disorders. They focus particularly on relapse, the long-term course of addiction to drugs or alcohol, and interventions to prevent relapse and promote recovery. A critical and highly complex public health problem, addiction is seen today as having biological, psychological, social, and cultural aspects. This important volume brings together the major perspectives on addiction, treatment, and recovery along with the current findings of clinical and scientific research.For those working with addicted patients and those making policy decisions that affect treatment and its availability, this book is an essential reference.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aSubstance abusexPatientsxRehabilitation. 0aSubstance abusexRelapsexPrevention. 7aSELF-HELP / Substance Abuse & Addictions / General.2bisacsh1 aAnglin, M. Douglas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBroome, Kirk M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Barry S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBühringer, Gerhard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCieslar, James R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCraddock, S. Gail, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDe Leon, George, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeMatteo, David S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/